Wow, Once again a beautiful video, from the very beginning to the very end.
All videos I watch on you tube is on 2x speed but when it comes to yours, it goes on regular speed and sometimes I pull back to see what you did twice or three times.
Super job I must say, always wanted to see how the fuel pump is swapped out and changed, as well as the charcoal canister.
I had on my Chevy a bad fuel pump and had it replaced, but I did not come with a new float having to go back and have the tank removed for the 2nd time to have the float put back, while I had issues when filling up the pump would just stop and I would need to re-click the pump around 10 times, assuming the charcoal canister and the vacuum system which vacuums all the fuel vapors was messed up so it sensed the tank was full or whatever it sensed to cause the pump to stop, while changing the fuel pump seemed to help the issue a bit, not complaining.

And well done cleaning the area where the battery sits, and the bolt
From under the muffler by the heat shield to keep it from sagging.

You moved the video along and explained each step in detail.
Assuming you gave it an oil change and changed the coolant, pads? Rotors? Transmission oil?

Would love to see a video on how to diagnose bad shocks, springs, struts, axles and tie rods and every other suspension part of the car, that's one of the main concerns when I buy a vehicle ,I have no clue what's going bad or what's bad.
And if the shocks or springs were supposed not be changed on the vehicle every x amount of miles and so on, assuming that's something you factor in when buying a vehicle?

Overall A+ with the video!
Super job!
Curios what does such a Manual cost you for the specs of the vehicle? Whether you buy a hard copy or online copy?

Thanks Chris for the amazing video! Keep it up! Job well done!

snippet.textDisplay:
About the breaker bar bit, here's a little trick if you don't have one. Get a deep socket that fits snug over the end of your ratchet, add a few extensions to the deep socket, and you're good to go. You shouldn't be putting that much torque into a ratchet though, or you'll break it. I've broken quite a few doing that, but if you've got the need for torque and don't have a breaker bar, then it works fine.


I'm also amazed that entire vehicle didn't catch fire with how bad it was melted. That could have definitely been a total loss.

snippet.textDisplay:
I did the same thing with my cousin's '84 Trans Am that he put an '89 body on. He just bought a new convertible BMW 3 Series and left his TA sitting for a year. He said it wouldn't start and it was dull and funky. I said, "How much do you want for it?" He told me to give him a hundred bucks. Without missing a beat, I pulled a $100 bill out of my wallet, handed it to him and went upstairs to get the title from my aunt. I had a tow truck there the next day and had her towed home.

48 hours later, I had it running and purring like a kitten (until I'd rev it and that Flowmaster exhaust roared like a tiger) with an hour of tinkering and she was all bright & shiny after a full day of hand compounding & waxing with Meguiar's. I detailed the interior, engine compartment & wheels of course.

The next day, I pulled up to him while he was (no lie) trying to get his BMW started! LOL

He said, 'oh, so that's why you wanted my car, for parts for your car'. I said "No...this IS your car!" He was shocked! He stood back and you could see his face grimace! My uncle laughed and slapped him on the shoulder and said, "You see! All that car needed was a little TLC!"

But my cousin was happy for me and for his former Trans Am; Better to have family get the benefit of it than a stranger.

Seems like everything back home is going up in price, except used cars. Shit! Wish I was back home in the states.
"...one screwdriver length..." No, kid..."one screwdriver-blade's thickness"...Don't get so carried away with your self-love that you lose accuracy of language. In technical matters, it is more important than almost anything else, including (perhaps especially) sounding like a self-appointed expert.
The vids you produce aren't bad, ( this is about the 3rd of yours I've watched) but you gear your presentation as if you were speaking to 4th graders while you unbox a new toy. You seem to assume NO ONE except you has ever touched a tool before. Enthusiasm is one thing...over-selling something as routine as taking nuts off of bolts is another.
My daughter used to watch Minecraft, and the only thing I detested about it was the yelling and screaming by the (young adult) idiots who were playing and had their pics displayed in the upper corners....and who screeched and howled their way through every vid. That's what you remind me of.
Maybe people have changed back home, maybe everyone DOES have the mentality of 4th graders...(I mean, the Dems DID get a lot of votes last time from the big welfare-sustained cities) but I personally feel your actual target audience is a little older, and more mature, and would probably enjoy your vids a little more if you showed them the respect they deserve by speaking to them as adults, and toning down the hysteria just a bit.
